# Project Convention Extensions Directory

This directory is where teams add their project-specific convention files during setup.

## Purpose

Project convention extensions define your team's standards and are loaded during
Construction phase to enforce those standards automatically. Unlike the framework's
built-in extensions (security/, documentation/), these files are authored by YOUR
team for YOUR project.

## Why This Directory Is Empty

This directory is intentionally empty in the framework repository. Each team creates
their own convention files here during project setup. The framework provides the
structure; your team provides the content.

## Common Convention Files

Teams typically create some or all of the following:

### folder-conventions.md
Your project's layering rules and what constitutes a violation.
- Which directories can import from which
- Architectural boundary enforcement
- Module organization rules

### api-conventions.md
Your API design standards.
- URL naming patterns
- Request/response conventions
- Error response formats
- Pagination standards
- Versioning rules

### naming-conventions.md
File, class, function, and schema naming rules.
- File naming (kebab-case, camelCase, etc.)
- Class and interface naming
- Function and method naming
- Database table and column naming
- Environment variable naming

### testing-conventions.md
Test structure, fixture rules, what may and may not be mocked.
- Test file organization
- Test naming conventions
- Fixture and factory patterns
- Mocking boundaries
- Coverage requirements

## How to Create Convention Files

See SETUP.md for detailed guidance on writing convention files for your project.

Each convention file should follow the extension format used by other extensions
(see extensions/security/ for examples):

1. Define rules with unique IDs (e.g., FOLDER-01, API-01)
2. Include verification criteria for each rule
3. Specify whether violations are blocking or advisory
4. Provide examples of compliant and non-compliant patterns

## Gitignore Note

This directory is gitignored in the framework repository so team convention files
are never accidentally committed to the framework. Your convention files live only
in your own project repository.

When you clone this framework to start a new project, you'll create your own
convention files here and commit them to YOUR project's repository.

## Reference

- Section 7 of the framework spec describes project convention extensions
- SETUP.md STEP 3 guides you through creating convention files
- extensions/security/baseline/ shows the structure to follow
